    </table>
</div>
</p>
<p>And this is the <em>second</em> reason you might decide to map the inverse side of the relation:
it's required if you're doing a JOIN in this direction.</p>
<div class="admonition tip"><p class="admonition-title"><span class="fa fa-lightbulb-o"></span> Tip</p><p>Actually, not true! As Stof suggested in the comments on this page, it <em>is</em> possible
to query over this join <em>without</em> mapping this side of the relationship, it just
takes a little bit more work:</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">$this-&gt;createQueryBuilder('genus')
    // ...
    -&gt;leftJoin(
        'AppBundle:GenusNote',
        'genus_note',
        \Doctrine\ORM\Query\Expr\Join::WITH,
        'genus = genus_note.genus'
    )
    // ...</code></pre>
</div><p>Back in <code>GenusRepository</code>, give <code>leftJoin()</code> a second argument: <code>genus_note</code> - this
is the alias we can use during the rest of the query to reference fields on the joined
<code>genus_note</code> table. This allows us to say <code>-&gt;orderBy('genus_note.createdAt', 'DESC')</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="b7609bb4d7">
    <div class="meta">
        <div class="actions">
            <span class="fa fa-clipboard js-activate-clipboard" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Copy Code" data-placement="top"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="info">
                        <span class="js-expand-all" data-range="1-24" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Show All Lines" data-placement="top">
                <i class="fa fa-expand js-icon-load-more"></i>
                <i class="fa fa-spinner fa-spin js-icon-loading"></i>
            </span>
            
            24 lines <span class="meta-divider"></span> <span title="src/AppBundle/Repository/GenusRepository.php">src/AppBundle/Repository/GenusRepository.php</span>
        </div>
    </div>
